lower serum and hair magnesium levels than children without ADHD. Further study may be needed to in-
vestigate the behavioral influence on ADHD due to lower magnesium levels, the association between brain and
serum magnesium levels, and the effects brought about by larger longitudinal cohort studies.
1. Introduction
ADHD is one of the world's most common neurodevelopmental
diseases of children, approximately 5% of all school-aged children
(Lange et al., 2017). This disorder is characterized by inattention, im-
pulsivity, and hyperactivity, which results in varying degrees of func-
tional and interpersonal impairment throughout one's life time. The
pathophysiology of ADHD is still obscure, although it is believed that
both genetic and environmental risk factors may be responsible for the
cause of this disorder (e.g., nutritional factors such as micronutrient
deficiencies of copper, iron, magnesium, and polyunsaturated fatty
acids (Arnsten, 2000, He et al., 2017).
Magnesium is an important cofactor in hundreds of enzymatic sys-
tems in our body, which includes signal transduction, protein synthesis,
electrical impulse transmission, neuromuscular conduction, carbohy-
drate metabolism (Kozielec and Starobrat-Hermelin, 1997), and blood
pressure modulation (Grober et al., 2015). Magnesium also plays a role
in ADHD-related neuro-transmission (e.g., dopamine, serotonin, and
NMDA-induced norepinephrine release). For example, it has been
shown that magnesium plays a role in activating tyrosine hydroxylase,
which is the rate-limiting enzyme in the process of dopamine synthesis
(Villagomez and Ramtekkar, 2014). Magnesium is also involved in
binding the receptors of serotonin and dopamine (Bloch and Mulqueen,
2014). Therefore, low magnesium levels may result in decreased do-
pamine synthesis and dysregulation of ADHD-related neuro-transmis-
sion.
Some of the symptoms of magnesium deficiency are similar to those
of ADHD, such as impaired cognitive processing, decreased attention
span, problems with concentration, increased exhaustion, hyperactivity
(especially in children), reduced reaction to external stimuli, irrit-
ability, insomnia, and increased aggression (Sinn, 2008). Other symp-
toms include increased exasperation, uncontrollable nervousness, and
deteriorating mood swings (Huss et al., 2010). Furthermore, symptoms
of familial hypomagnesemia, such as inattention, are also similar to
those of ADHD (Guran et al., 2011). Because many of these symptoms
share features with the symptoms of ADHD, some researches have hy-
pothesized that magnesium may account for some part of the patho-
genesis of ADHD.
Some studies have discussed the lower levels of magnesium detected
in serum and erythrocytes of children with ADHD (Grober et al., 2015).
Kozielec et al. detected magnesium deficiency in 95% of his study
subjects, especially in hair, red blood cell, and serum samples (Kozielec
and Starobrat-Hermelin, 1997). Mahmoud et al. discovered similar
findings, in which 72% of Egyptian ADHD children studied had in-
sufficient levels of magnesium (Mahmoud et al., 2011). Similar findings
were also made in the work of Elbaz et al. (Elbaz et al., 2017).
On the other hand, some researchers did not come up with same
results as those mentioned above. Irmisch et al. did not find a sig-
nificant lack of Mg among ADHD patients (Irmisch et al., 2011). For
their study, 9 boys with ADHD (8.2 ± 0.6 years) and 11 controls
(7.9 ± 0.87 years) were recruited, and blood serum Mg and several
lipoproteins were measured. Mg levels were higher than in the control
group. Similar findings concerning high Mg levels were also made in
the study by Antalis et al. (2006). In this study, 12 adults with ADHD
(24.3 ± 2.3 years) and 12 controls (22.3 ± 2.4 years) were recruited.
Seventy-five percent of subjects with ADHD took stimulant medication,
whereas 50% of subjects with ADHD took vitamin/mineral supple-
ments, in contrast with 25% of controls. Significantly higher serum
magnesium concentrations were found in the ADHD group.
In 2012, Scassellati C. et al. published a systematic review of studies
examining the association between magnesium deficiency and ADHD.
However, they did not perform meta-analyses since there were only
three studies reported altered serum magnesium levels in patients
compared with controls (Scassellati et al., 2012). Because several stu-
dies presenting new evidence have been published since 2012, we
consequently conducted a meta-analysis to include the more recent data
and to reexamine the connection between magnesium insufficiency and
ADHD.
2. Methods and materials
We
followed
the
Meta-analysis
Of
Observational
Studies
in
Epidemiology (MOOSE) guidelines (Stroup et al., 2000) (see Supple-
mental Table 1). This preliminary meta-analysis followed an a priori
defined but unpublished protocol. The current meta-analysis complied
with the requirements of the Institutional Review Board of the Kaoh-
siung Municipal Kai-Syuan Psychiatric Hospital (KSPH-N-201706).
2.1. Search strategy and study selection
Two well-trained authors (BY Zeng and PT Tseng) independently
performed a systematic literature search from the study's inception until
October 27th, 2018. The following keywords were used in our search:
“(Magnesium OR Mg) AND (attention deficit hyperactivity disorder OR
ADHD OR hyperkinesia OR hyperkinetic disorder)” on PubMed,
ProQuest, and ClinicalKey platforms. A similar search was also con-
ducted in Embase, ScienceDirect, Cochrane Library, Web of Science,
and ClinicalTrials.gov databases (Supplemental Fig. 1). The reference
lists of included articles and recent reviews were also searched to
identify additional articles (Ghanizadeh, 2013; Grober et al., 2015;
Hariri and Azadbakht, 2015; Scassellati et al., 2012; Villagomez and
Ramtekkar, 2014).
These authors (BY Zeng and PT Tseng) independently screened the
titles and abstracts of all retrieved results for potential eligibility, then
reviewed full-text articles of potentially eligible papers and compiled a
final list of included studies. Any inconsistencies were resolved through
discussion with a third reviewer, YH Huang.
2.2. Eligibility criteria
Inclusion criteria were (a) observational studies, including a cohort
or cross-sectional study design comparing peripheral levels of magne-
sium in children with ADHD and controls, and (b) trials in humans. The
exclusion criteria included: (a) preclinical studies, review articles,
meeting abstracts, and non-human studies; (b) studies not related to
magnesium levels in children with ADHD; (c) studies lacking adequate
control; and (d) studies using children not definitely diagnosed for
ADHD.
2.3. Data extraction
The two authors (BY Zeng and PT Tseng) independently extracted
data of interest following the MOOSE guidelines. Primary outcomes
were the differences in magnesium levels in children with ADHD when
compared to control groups (calculated as Hedges' g statistic and cor-
responding 95% confidence intervals (CIs) and p values). The control
groups were defined as those without ADHD. When data were not
available from the included studies, we contacted the primary authors
to request the original data. We contacted the authors via email on two
occasions, if required. A second email was sent a week later, if the
Y.-H. Huang et al.
Progress in Neuropsychopharmacology & Biological Psychiatry 90 (2019) 134–141
135
limited email received no response. If there was no relevant data in the
paper regarding magnesium levels, wherever possible, we attempted to
use another compatible statistical parameter (e.g. “p value and sample
sizes” or “odds ratio”) to estimate the ESs according to the protocol in
the Comprehensive Meta-Analysis manuals and guidance on the
Comprehensive Meta-Analysis website: (https://www.meta-analysis.
com/downloads/Meta-analysis%20Converting%20among%20effect
%20sizes.pdf) to covert and pool the ESs into Hedges' g.
We extracted the variables of interest, included magnesium levels,
mean age, gender distribution (percentage of females), and the types of
assay used for detection of magnesium levels.
2.4. Methodological quality appraisal
We used the modified Newcastle-Ottawa scale (NOS) to evaluate the
quality of included studies. Briefly, the modified NOS was based on a
version previously used in a meta-analysis study published in the British
Journal of Psychiatry in 2013. Scores ranged from zero to nine
(Supplemental Table 2) (Anglin et al., 2013). Studies would be identi-
fied as representing at high risk of bias if their scores were less than five
points (Luchini et al., 2017).
2.5. Meta-analysis procedure
Given the anticipated heterogeneity in the basic population of this
study, we conducted the meta-analysis with a random effects, rather
than a fixed effect, model (Borenstein et al., 2010). Because of pre-
sumed different units used among each study we choose the Hedges' g
with 95% CIs to compare our effect sizes (ESs) of our primary outcome
rather than difference in means. We defined the ESs to indicate “lower
magnesium levels in ADHD children than in controls” when the value of
Hedges' g was less than zero. The current meta-analysis was conducted
using the Comprehensive Meta-Analysis software, version 3 (Biostat,
Englewood, NJ). The threshold for statistical significance was set at a
two-tailed p-value < .05.
2.5.1. Sensitivity test, heterogeneity, and publication bias
We used sensitivity test with a “one study removal” test to evaluate
whether or not the results of the meta-analyses were resulted from any
outliers within the recruited studies (Tobias, 1999). Heterogeneity was
assessed by the Cochran Q test and its corresponding p value (Higgins
and Thompson, 2002). The I2 statistic was interpreted as the proportion
of heterogeneity a study estimates was due to heterogeneity (Borenstein
et al., 2017). We assessed publication bias via inspection of funnel plots
in situations of less than ten datasets (Higgins and Green, 2011) and
with the Egger's regression test in situation of more than ten datasets
(Egger et al., 1997). When evidence of publication bias was found, the
Duval and Tweedie's trim-and-fill procedure, which is a validated
model to estimate an ES, was employed (Duval and Tweedie, 2000).
2.5.2. Subgroup meta-analysis and meta-regression
Subgroup analysis were conducted to determine whether results
differed as we grouped them according to the sample sources (e.g.
blood, hair) or according to studies with definite diagnostic criteria for
diagnosis of ADHD (e.g. DSM (Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of
Mental Disorders) system or ICD (International Classification of Disease
system). Furthermore, because of the potential effect of “magnesome”
on the different magnesium levels between serum and plasma levels
(Piovesan et al., 2012), we further subdivided the blood samples into
serum and plasma subgroups. We performed subgroup analyses when-
ever data from at least three independent datasets were available
(Davey et al., 2011). We performed meta-regression analyses with un-
restricted maximum likelihood random-effects when data on each po-
tential moderator was provided by at least five different studies.
3. Results
3.1. Study selection
Fig. 1 summarizes details of the search results. In brief, a total of
twenty-seven studies entered the full-text review stage. Fifteen articles
were excluded for various reasons, including case report/case series
(Guran et al., 2011), being an adulthood but not pediatric study
(Antalis et al., 2006), lack of adequate control (Huss et al., 2010;
