articles is presented in Supplemental Table 3. In total, twelve articles
met the inclusion criteria. Details are summarized in Table 1 (An et al.,
2005; Archana et al., 2012; Baza et al., 2016; Bener et al., 2014; Dura-
Trave and Gallinas-Victoriano, 2014; Dura Trave et al., 2014; Elbaz
et al., 2017; Irmisch et al., 2011; Kamal et al., 2014; Mahmoud et al.,
2011; Tippairote et al., 2017).
3.2. Characteristics of included studies
Of the included studies, a total of 2872 children with ADHD (mean
age = 10.2, mean female proportion = 30.4%) and 2838 controls
(mean age = 10.1, mean female proportion = 39.4%) were included.
Of the sample sources provided, eight provided comparisons of the
differences of peripheral magnesium levels in ADHD children and
controls in blood [six for serum (Baza et al., 2016, Bener et al., 2014,
Elbaz et al., 2017, Irmisch et al., 2011, Kamal et al., 2014, Mahmoud
et al., 2011), one for plasma (An et al., 2005) with a total of seven
datasets, and one for whole blood (Yang et al., 2018)], four for hair
with a total of four datasets (An et al., 2005; Baza et al., 2016; Elbaz
et al., 2017; Tippairote et al., 2017), one for saliva with a total of two
datasets (Archana et al., 2012), and two for food intake with a total of
two datasets (Dura-Trave and Gallinas-Victoriano, 2014; Dura-Trave
and Gallinas-Victoriano, 2014). When there were fewer than three
datasets, a meta-analytic procedure regarding saliva or food intake was
not performed.
Among the recruited studies, the diagnosis of ADHD was made ac-
cording to definite diagnostic criteria, such as the Diagnostic and
Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fourth Edition (DSM-IV)
(Association, 1994) or Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental
Disorders, Fifth Edition (DSM-5) (Association, 2013), except for two
studies. These two studies (Irmisch et al., 2011; Kamal et al., 2014)
defined ADHD based upon clinicians' diagnoses, together with the
Conners' Teacher Rating Scale (Purpura and Lonigan, 2009).
3.3. Methodological quality of included studies
Regarding the methodological quality of included studies, the
average NOS score was 7.2 with standard deviation (SD) = 0.7
(Supplemental Table 2).
3.4. Meta-analysis of differences of peripheral magnesium levels in children
with ADHD and controls without ADHD: with regard to blood (including
plasma, serum, and whole blood)
Eight articles provided seven datasets in this part of the meta-ana-
lysis. The meta-analysis suggested that peripheral blood magnesium
levels, either in plasma, serum, or whole blood, among children diag-
nosed with ADHD were significantly lower than those in controls
(k = 8, Hedges' g = −0.547, 95% CI = −0.818 to −0.276, p < .001;
mean difference = −0.142 mg/dl, 95% CI = −0.215 to −0.070)
(Fig. 2) with significant heterogeneity (Q value = 90.925, df = 7,
I2 = 92.301%, p < .001) but not significant publication bias as de-
termined via inspection of funnel plot (Supplemental Fig. 2A).
3.4.1. Sensitivity test
Significant results of the meta-analysis would not change into in-
significance after removing any one of the recruited studies. Therefore,
the significant results of this part of meta-analysis might not have been
contributed to any outliers among the recruited studies.
3.4.2. Meta-regression
Due to lack of data, meta-regression would be performed only on
associations between ESs and mean age and mean female proportion.
To be specific, there was a significantly inverse association between ESs
and mean female proportion (slope = −0.017, p = .001, k = 8) but not
mean age (p = .456), which meant the higher the mean female pro-
portion, the lower the ESs (i.e. lower differences of blood Mg levels
between ADHD children and controls).
